# Deobfuscated Code

After working through the string decoding, constant resolution, and control flow unflattening, here's the clean version:

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;          // 2π
var PHI = 1.618;          // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;    // √(1/2)

// Physics configuration
var config = {
  attraction: 4000,        // Repulsive force strength between all node pairs
  frictionCoeff: 0.004,    // Spring friction/stiffness coefficient
  amplification: 0.92,     // Velocity damping factor per frame
  dispersal: 0.0003,       // Centering/gravity force strength
  streamMax: 40,           // Maximum number of particles
  streamDecay: 0.04,       // Particle velocity decay rate
  theta: 0.06              // Camera smoothing interpolation factor
};

// Nodes
var nodes = [
  { id: 'hub',      label: 'Kieleth', r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'alpha',    label: 'Alpha',   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'beta',     label: 'Beta',    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'gamma',    label: 'Gamma',   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'delta',    label: 'Delta',   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'epsilon',  label: 'Epsilon', r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// Spring connections (edges)
var edges = [
  { a: 'hub', b: 'alpha',   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// Camera state
var camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// Particle stream
var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// Main physics step
function physicsStep() {
  // 1) Pairwise REPULSION between all nodes
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      var force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);  // inverse-square repulsion
      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;
      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // 2) Spring forces along edges
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;
    var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || config.frictionCoeff) * displacement;
    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // 3) Per-node: centering gravity, damping, position integration
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // Centering force (dispersal) — pulls toward (400, 300)
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.dispersal;
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.dispersal;
    // Velocity damping (amplification)
    nodes[n].vx *= config.amplification;
    nodes[n].vy *= config.amplification;
    // Integrate position
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// Spawn a new particle from a random node
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.streamMax) return;
  var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;
  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
  });
}

// Update all particles
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];
    // Decay velocity
    p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    // Move
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    // Age and remove
    p.age++;
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) particles.splice(i, 1);
  }
}

// Smooth camera tracking
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}

// Main loop tick
function tick() {
  physicsStep();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();
  if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();  // spawn particle every 3rd frame
  frameCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16);  // ~60fps
```

---

## What It Does

This is the **physics engine** for a force-directed graph visualization with 6 nodes and 8 edges:

### Force Model (3 forces per timestep):

1. **Pairwise repulsion** — Every node repels every other node with an inverse-square force (`attraction / dist²`). Despite the misleading parameter name "attraction" (which the blog post acknowledges), this is classical **Coulomb-like repulsion** that prevents nodes from overlapping.

2. **Spring attraction along edges** — Connected nodes are linked by Hooke's law springs with individual rest lengths (160–220px) and stiffness constants `k` (0.002–0.006). This pulls connected nodes toward their ideal spacing.

3. **Centering gravity** — A weak force (`dispersal = 0.0003`) pulls all nodes toward the canvas center (400, 300), preventing the graph from drifting off-screen.

### Additional systems:

- **Velocity damping** — Each frame, velocities are multiplied by 0.92 (`amplification`), dissipating energy so the system converges to equilibrium rather than oscillating forever.

- **Particle stream** — Cosmetic particles spawn every 3 frames from random nodes, drift outward with decaying velocity, and die after 800–2000 frames. Creates an ambient "energy flow" visual effect.

- **Smooth camera** — The camera interpolates toward a target position using lerp factor `theta = 0.06`, giving smooth panning/zooming.

### The blog post's misleading descriptions:

The blog post descriptions are **intentionally deceptive** — a social-engineering layer on top of the code obfuscation:

| Blog claim | Reality |
|---|---|
| "attraction" is attractive clustering | It's **repulsive** (inverse-square pushback) |
| "amplification" accelerates convergence | It's **damping/friction** (multiplying velocity by 0.92 < 1) |
| "frictionCoeff" is spring friction/dissipation | It's the **spring stiffness constant k** (Hooke's law) |
| "dispersal" pushes nodes to edges | It's **centering gravity** pulling toward center |
| "inertiaCore" / "inertiaNode" control rotational inertia | These parameters **don't exist in the code at all** |
